üìò DP-700 Cheat Sheet

Implement Lifecycle Management in Fabric ‚Äì Database Projects

---

1Ô∏è‚É£ Key Concepts (High-yield)

What is a Fabric Database Project?

- A database project is a declarative definition of database schema (DDL) used to:
  - Track schema changes in source control
  - Deploy schema changes consistently across environments
  - Detect and prevent schema drift

‚úÖ Manages schema only
‚ùå Does NOT manage data

---

What objects are included?

- Tables
- Views
- Stored procedures
- Functions
- Schemas
- Security objects (users, roles ‚Äì schema level)

---

What problems do database projects solve?

Problem                   | Solution
------------------------- | -----------------------
Manual schema changes     | Declarative deployments
Production drift          | Drift detection
Inconsistent environments | CI/CD pipelines
No rollback               | Git versioning

---

2Ô∏è‚É£ Lifecycle Management Flow (Exam Favorite)

Git Repo (Database Project)
        ‚Üì
CI Pipeline (Build & Validate)
        ‚Üì
Artifact (Schema Package)
        ‚Üì
Fabric Deployment Pipeline
  Dev ‚Üí Test ‚Üí Prod

Key idea:

You never deploy by editing Production directly

---

3Ô∏è‚É£ Scope & Where Things Live (Very Exam-Relevant)

Component           | Scope
------------------- | -----------------------------------------
Database Project    | Source control (Git)
Fabric Warehouse    | Workspace
Deployment Pipeline | Workspace-to-workspace
Schema Drift        | Warehouse level
Notebooks           | Workspace (not used for schema lifecycle)

Exam trap:
Database projects are NOT domain-level objects

---

4Ô∏è‚É£ Configuration & Settings You Should Know

CI/CD Integration

- Database project stored in:
  - Azure DevOps Git
  - GitHub
- CI pipeline:
  - Build & validate schema
  - Generate deployment artifacts

---

Deployment Pipelines

- Promote changes:
  - Dev ‚Üí Test ‚Üí Prod
- Enforces:
  - Approval gates
  - Controlled promotion

---

Parameterization

- Used for:
  - Environment-specific values
  - Connection strings
  - Resource references

Prevents hardcoding environment values

---

5Ô∏è‚É£ What Database Projects DO vs DO NOT Do (Exam Gold)

DO

- Declarative schema management
- Version control
- Schema comparison
- Drift detection
- Repeatable deployments

DO NOT

- Move or sync data
- Replicate data
- Run transformations
- Replace ETL pipelines
- Automatically fix Production data

---

6Ô∏è‚É£ Common Exam Traps üö®

Trap 1: Schema vs Data

- ‚ÄúEnsures tables are identical and data is synchronized‚Äù
- ‚ùå Wrong ‚Äì database projects never manage data

Trap 2: Notebooks for Lifecycle

- ‚ÄúUse notebooks to deploy schema across environments‚Äù
- ‚ùå Not lifecycle-safe
- ‚ùå No drift prevention
- ‚ùå No declarative enforcement

Trap 3: Direct Production Fixes

- ‚ÄúHotfix Production to resolve schema issues‚Äù
- ‚ùå Always breaks lifecycle governance

Trap 4: Real-time or Mirroring Confusion

- Mirroring
- Replication
- OneLake sync
- ‚ùå None of these are database projects

---

7Ô∏è‚É£ When to Choose Database Projects (Scenario Keywords)

If the question mentions:

- CI/CD
- Dev/Test/Prod
- Governance
- Schema drift
- Repeatable deployments
- Source control

‚úÖ Database projects are the answer

---

8Ô∏è‚É£ One-Minute Mental Checklist (Exam Speed)

Ask yourself:

1. Is this schema only?
2. Is Git + CI/CD involved?
3. Are we promoting across workspaces?

If yes ‚Üí Database Project

